@0xdade As for macOS, I believe that Apple's automated device enrollment for MDM for organizations can help here (pre-enroll before the device is taken out of the box):

https://t.co/RdvbyvBUIR

Then you can deliver device certificates via SCEP.

@arekfurt App-layer encryption is a pretty good way to add a 2nd layer of defense when datastores are 1 misconfig away from being public: 

https://t.co/sDStUI1Oji

Should be considered mandatory for sensitive direct identifiers. Has almost zero overhead because every CPU has AES-NI now.

RT @philvenables: "The beginner chases the right answers. 

The master chases the right questions." 

@JamesClear

@joshcorman @RosenzweigP @jkouns I think it was the RSA 2010 panel on Responsible Disclosure as mentioned here: 

https://t.co/LtkcH9Ywkh

but that seems to be beyond the horizon of what the Internet remembers and can't find much else about it.

@UK_Daniel_Card I am basically wondering if patterns from production infra could apply to AD. Here is AWS description of cell-based architecture: 

https://t.co/kzlazm3Fgn

For the domains that host joined, they are spread across N fixed-size domains. Admin privs over hosts are contained.

@eatonphil It's 25 years old, but I really enjoyed reading this book straight through:

https://t.co/8Hpw8F3R1R

File systems don't change all that quickly, most of the content in here should still be relevant for the local file systems in use today, especially b/c BFS was that far ahead.

@nojonesuk Absolutely a fair question. I really liked Amazon's whitepaper on the arch of their KMS: https://t.co/QiUQyToK2A

Okta also has good architectural details (esp w.r.t. multi-tenancy) in their whitepaper: https://t.co/ZfOBuzVsfV

I'd love to see similar for AWS Identity Center/SSO.

@dfaranha @assolini Makes sense. The linked article quotes some numbers: 

"One organized gang alone in Brazil was able to SIM swap 5,000 victims. At Mozambique‚Äôs largest bank they had a monthly average of 17.2 cases of SIM swap fraud."

So a problem, but still in the targeted &lt;10k/year bucket.

@clancynewyork I don't think the reality has materially changed since then (password stuffing still extremely prevalent, SIM swaps hard to target and scale, etc.)

Here is some more on these findings from 2019:

https://t.co/kfhoUq0WuI

@lorenzofb At least in the US, FB use is falling sharply among younger generations: 

https://t.co/s29YdpdlHY

Yes, in favor of TikTok, but that's a very different type of social media (oriented towards "creators") rather than update sharing.
